omf updateÊ[omf]Ê[<package>...]
Update Oh My Fish, all package repositories, and all installed packages.
When called without arguments, update core and all installed packages.
You can choose to update only the core, by runningÊomf update omf.
For selective package update, list only the names of packages you wish to update. You may still include "omf" in the list to update the core as well.
Oh My Fish installer adds a snippet to fish's user config files (~/.config/fish/conf.d/) which calls OMF's startup code.
Notice that the scripts in that directory are sourced in the order that the filesystem sees them, and so it may be necessary to prefix your script files with ordering numbers.
For example:Êa_script.fishÊwill take precedence over theÊomf.fishÊsnippet. So ifÊa_script.fishÊdepends on plugins managed by OMF, consider renaming the script file toÊxx_a_script.fish.
Similiarly, to make sure that a script runs beforeÊomf.fish, you may prefix it withÊ00_. Alternatively,Ê~/.config/omf/before.init.fishÊmay be used.
# Golang developers might need this one
set -xg GOPATH $HOME/gocode
# Python developers otherwise
set -xg PYTHONDONTWRITEBYTECODE 1
In fish 2.2, there is noÊconf.dÊdirectory, so the startup code has to be placed in the fish config file (~/.config/fish/config.fish).

Oh My Fish can scaffold a package structure for you. Use the commandÊomf new
To learn package creation let's create a new package that will provide aÊhello_worldÊcommand for your shell. Package names may only contain lowercase letters and hyphens to separate words.
$ omf new plugin hello_world
$ ls -l
README.md
init.fish
functions/hello_world.fish
completions/hello_world.fish
Always describe how your package works in theÊREADME.md.
Also read more aboutÊauto completionÊand take care to provide it for your utilities when applicable.
functions/hello_world.fishÊdefines a single function:
function hello_world -d "Prints hello world"
echo "Hello World!"
end

Each function in your package must be declared in its own file underÊfunctionsÊdirectory. This is required by fish autoloading mechanism, which loads functions on demand, avoiding loading unused functions at startup time.
Hooks

Oh My Fish provides a "hooks" system that allows you to write scripts for your package that run when other interesting events occur. Packages can use these hooks to provide advanced installation, custom resource management, etc. Hooks are ordinary Fish scripts named after the event they are triggered by. Most hooks reside in aÊhooksÊdirectory inside a package's project directory.

Hooks that are called at startup time (init.fishÊandÊkey_bindings.fish) can slow down shell startup. Be sure to avoid slow code at startup time! Also, if your package doesn't need a hook file, be sure to remove it.
The working directory inside a hook is always set to the root directory of the package. The hooks Oh My Fish currently supports are listed below:
